    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "The basic logs would be what geth spits out on the commandline. If you run geth with e.g. \r\n`geth  &> log.txt` , you should get some more info. \r\n\r\nThere are also options to increase the verbosity for certain areas, but that would be a good start. Personally, I've noticed that when there's a slow disk, it results in peers being dropped since the disk issues cause you to become an unresponsive peer. \r\n\r\nTo see what kind of speeds you're getting, this can be a good start. On my ssd:  \r\n```\r\n$dd if=/dev/zero of=/tmp/output conv=fdatasync bs=384k count=1k; rm -f /tmp/output\r\n1024+0 records in\r\n1024+0 records out\r\n402653184 bytes (403 MB, 384 MiB) copied, 0,944079 s, 427 MB/s\r\n```",
